{"key":"processedPost-4620260","value":{"id":4620260,"first":4606490,"last":4628208,"when":1125881767,"utime":"09/05/05 03:56 AM","cleanedPost":"Yea, cotton is good fungi food.  It can be used 'as is' as a substrate material.  It's about on a par with coir.  However, on the bra project, it was soaked in plain water at 160F for an hour. It was then wrapped around a five gallon bucket with the snap hooked on the back side of the bucket.  The cups were filled with compost and spawned with rye grain.  The padded cotton of the cups served as the casing layer.   It was then left on the five gallon bucket in a mini greenhouse until it had fruited.  As Paul Harvey used to say, now you know the rest of the story.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/05-13/208962316-Bunny_006qa.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/05-13/208962316-thumb_Bunny_006qa.jpg\"></a>"}}